    <section class="topic-section">
        <h2>The Basics of Taxes</h2>
        <p>Taxes are mandatory contributions levied by the government on your income, property, and purchases. These funds are used for public services like roads, schools, and emergency services. As a college student, you might encounter several types of taxes:</p>
        <ol>
            <li>Income Tax: Tax on the money you earn from jobs, including part-time and full-time work, internships, and freelance work.</li>
            <li>Sales Tax: A tax on purchased goods and services, which varies by state and locality.</li>
            <li>Property Tax: If you own property, you'll pay taxes on its value, but this is less common for students.</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="topic-section">
        <h2>Filing Tax Returns</h2>
        <p>Do You Need to File? Generally, if your income exceeds a certain threshold, you need to file a tax return. This threshold varies based on factors like your age, dependency status, and the type of income you receive.</p>
        <p>Important Documents: W-2 Form, 1099 Form, etc.</p>
        <p>The Process: Filing a tax return involves reporting your income and calculating your tax liability. You can file taxes electronically or by mail, and there are various software tools and services to assist with this process.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="topic-section">
        <h2>Understanding Tax Deductions and Credits</h2>
        <p>Deductions reduce your taxable income, while tax credits directly reduce the amount of tax you owe. Common deductions and credits for students include educational expenses and credits like the American Opportunity Tax Credit and Lifetime Learning Credit.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="topic-section">
        <h2>Managing Your Taxes</h2>
        <p>Stay Organized: Keep all your tax-related documents in order.</p>
        <p>Educate Yourself: Stay informed about tax laws and use reliable resources like the IRS website.</p>
        <p>Seek Help If Needed: Don't hesitate to seek help from university tax assistance or a tax professional if you're unsure about your tax situation.</p>
    </section>

